Experiments with Random Forests

The following workflow includes the coding of a random forest model to create a model that will help predict the market direction for the years following 2019. The random forest model generates multiple base models in parallel. For each tree split, a sample of the predictors are used.

# Load necessary libraries 
library(tidyverse)
library(tidymodels)
library(doParallel)
library(knitr)
library(scales)
library(vip)
library(ranger)

NASDAQdt <- read_csv("nasdaq_lagged_2015_2019.csv")

Just like the boosting model, the same metrics are used, and the same process of splitting the data stays the same as well. Similarly, the cross-validation, and the choice of steps in the recipes.

# Data Metrics
data_metrics <- metric_set(roc_auc, precision, recall, accuracy)

# Data Splits
set.seed(2673)
NASDAQdt_split <- initial_split(NASDAQdt, prop = 0.75, strata = Up_Down)
NASDAQ_train <- training(NASDAQdt_split)
NASDAQ_test <- testing(NASDAQdt_split)
# Cross-validation folds 
set.seed(548)
NASDAQ_folds <- vfold_cv(NASDAQ_train, v = 5, repeats = 5, strata = Up_Down)
# Pre-processing Recipes 
# Base Recipe
rf_base_recipe <- recipe(Up_Down ~ ., data = NASDAQdt) %>%
    step_zv(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
    step_corr(all_numeric_predictors())
# Enhanced Recipe 
rf_enhanced_recipe <- recipe(Up_Down ~ ., data = NASDAQdt) %>%
  step_zv(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_corr(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_YeoJohnson(all_numeric_predictors())

As mentioned in the boosting workbook, the year should not be a predictor because it does not change the market direction. However, the year is a variable that is still important to consider in our analysis overall as it help with seasonality trends.

When creating the rf model, we tune the trees and mtry elements as this searches for the combination of trees and mtry values that result in the best model performance, as measured by roc_auc. The impurity importance element in the creation of the model is important as it determines the best split at each node for random variables (importance = impurity).

# Create Model 
rf_model <-
    rand_forest(trees = tune(), mtry = tune()) %>%
    set_mode(('classification')) %>%
    set_engine('ranger', importance = "impurity")
# Define Hyper-parameters 
rf_grid <- grid_regular(
    trees(),
    finalize(mtry(), NASDAQ_train),
    levels = c(5,5))
# Define workflow 
rf_workflow_base <-
    workflow() %>%
    add_recipe(rf_base_recipe) %>%
    add_model(rf_model)

rf_workflow_enhanced <-
    workflow() %>%
    add_recipe(rf_enhanced_recipe) %>%
    add_model(rf_model)
# Tune the Model 
# Start a cluster
number_of_cores <- parallel::detectCores(logical = FALSE)
cluster <- makeForkCluster(number_of_cores)
registerDoParallel(cluster)

rf_control <- control_resamples(save_pred = TRUE)

rf_results_base <-
    rf_workflow_base %>%
    tune_grid(
        NASDAQ_folds,
        grid = rf_grid,
        metrics = data_metrics,
        control = rf_control
    )

rf_control <- control_resamples(save_pred = TRUE)

rf_results_enhanced <-
    rf_workflow_enhanced %>%
    tune_grid(
        NASDAQ_folds,
        grid = rf_grid,
        metrics = data_metrics,
        control = rf_control
    )

# Stop a cluster
stopCluster(cluster)

Results

  show_best(metric = 'roc_auc') %>%

# Visualize results 
rf_metrics <- rf_results_enhanced %>%
    collect_metrics()

rf_metrics %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = mtry, y = mean, color = trees)) +
    geom_point() +
    facet_wrap(~ .metric, scales = 'free_y', ncol = 1) +
    labs(title = 'Random Forest Performance',
         x = 'Number of Sampled Predictors',
         y = 'Mean Performance') +
    theme_minimal()

# Confusion Matrix 
# Select best model 
rf_best <- rf_results_enhanced %>%
    select_best(metric = 'roc_auc')

rf_best %>%
